50|$|Outside of the United States the {{international}} <b>Euro-Commercial</b> <b>Paper</b> Market has over $500 billion in outstandings, {{made up of}} instruments denominated predominately in euros, dollars and sterling.|$|E
50|$|Euro debt {{securities}} are securities issued internationally outside their domestic market in a denomination {{different from that}} of the issuer's domicile. They include eurobonds and euronotes. Eurobonds are characteristically underwritten, and not secured, and interest is paid gross. A euronote may take the form of <b>euro-commercial</b> <b>paper</b> (ECP) or euro-certificates of deposit.|$|E
50|$|In 1971, Yassukovich hired Von Clemm to join White Weld, {{first as}} a {{temporary}} consultant on the feasibility of a <b>Euro-commercial</b> <b>paper</b> market, which did not catch on. However in 1972 Von Clemm effectively gave up his academic career to concentrate on banking full-time. He had an aggressive style - for example on one occasion printing up T-shirts for staff which read Buy Bonds. He was also said to effectively bully clients into taking on the bank.|$|E

